values:
I'm starting to look at this whole Live Journal as a bad thing. At first I thought it would be a good way for all of us to keep in touch when we leave, but now all I think of it as is a a breeding ground for distrust and sadness. It is a gossip center. Some of you may post what happened to you to day or plans to do stuff later on, but the true reason anyone looks at this is to find out what people think about, be it  about themselves or about other people. 

The whole top ten thing, although you may be finally telling someone what you wanted to for so long, you're also telling everyone else. If you truly wanted someone to know how you felt, go to them face to face. I made the mistake of not doing that before, it turned bad, but luckily it worked out. If you can't tell them face to face, maybe its better that they don't know then, for if it was truly something important and loving, then what should you be afraid of. What this really is to me, is saying goodbye.

I believe the same thing that Matt does. Don't look at this summer as our last and as if this is goodbye. There is no goodbye in our world, only cya later. Somehow, someway we will keep in touch, or see each other again. Don't look into the future being scared. Look at it as an adventure. Don't cling to the past either, embrace it for what it has taught you and remember it fondly as you travel down the road. Clinging to the old will just leave you alone later on when the world has open its doors for you to start truly living. This is just the beginning of our lives, who knows what is really out there.

I don't mean to say that I won't miss you all, I will, but I have faith in our friendships and that we will always stay together.

This will be the last journal entry I ever make.

For any of those who wish to keep in touch with me, email me your Phone Numbers, Address, Screen name, and College you are attending at Genjackel@gmail.com

I love you all and I'll cya later. 

The door is open, my pockets are full of memories, and I'm stepping through to the unknown...

I don't think Ive ever been so frightened in my life. I can't even imagine what it was like for those who were actually there. But I think the worst part for me is that I wasn't there. There was nothing i could have done to help, there was nothing I could have done period. I could have come back home and lost one of my closest, if not the closest of my friends.... If you don't know what or who I'm talking about, don't ask for I'm not the one to retell the story. But before I heard the news, it was a good day. I mean it was afterwords too, just not nearly as much. We left NC at 8:45 this morning. Brad, Michael, and I drove for about 5 hours before stopping at a little restaurant called Hot Weiners. The restaurant seats about 8 people and was packed. We ordered hot dogs and went outside to eat. The owner came out, told us he was sorry it was so packed and to make it up, gave me a free t-shirt. Then we hit the road again, stopping only for gas, food, and classic coke in a bottle. We listened to cheesy 90's music, cartoon theme songs, and of course, incubus. we got home a little before 8:30, stopped into see my parents, then left to celebrate daivds birthday. Thats where I heard the story. After that, the rest of the crew showed up including David and we headed to steak n Shake. We had all chipped in and bought David and iPod Shuffle, which I think he liked. After that we hung out around Brad's house, then Justin, Chelsea, and I drove around for a bit and talked before heading home. After a 12 hour drive, I'm wide awake and no where close to getting to sleep. Guess I'll watch tv/do the laundry/write thank you cards for grad party. Peace Out -Andrew

So today started off with us getting up around 9 and heading out to the ocean. The waves were nice and strong and we did a lot of body surfing. Although, one of the waves was strong, followed by an even stronger second wave. I rode the first, smashed by the second, flipped underwater backwards, smashed my head into the ground head and then flipped again to have my shoulder scrape along the bottom giving me some cuts. It was sweet.

As the day progressed we ended up digging a large hole in the sand and playing hold the hole. The object is to get a ball and the person holding the ball in the circle, with the ball touching the bottom. No rules after that. It was full of lots of tackling and flipping. I sprained my toe in around the 3rd point of the second game, but went on to win anyways. It was sweet too.

We ended up heading to a seafood restaurant for dinner. they were famous for crap, but I wanted more then that so I ordered a seafood platter. It was wussy, small portions of small food. Luckily I was able to mooch off my friends and get some tasty crab legs... mmm meat. 

What can I say but injuries make things much more fun.

Peace Out

-Andrew

It's weird to be away from home from so long, its like a precollege experience for me. I'll be here till fri, when we will leave in the early morning and probably get home around 11. 

miss all of you left at home, cya when i get there and enjoy matts pool. I have one like it here only its 1000 time bigger and its full of salt.

Andrew
